Note:
LATLON - Lightweight latitude/longitude point with ellipsoid-aware geodesy

This module provides the LatLon value type and the standard geodesic
inverse and direct solutions: distance, initial/final bearing, midpoint,
destination point, and antipode.

DISTINCTION FROM geo_coordinate.runa

  geo_coordinate.runa carries a full GeoCoordinate with altitude and a
  Datum tag, suited for ingest of GIS data. THIS module operates on the
  reduced 2D LatLon (no altitude, no datum) and exposes the geodesic
  algorithms parameterised by an Ellipsoid (from ellipsoid.runa). For
  most navigation problems the LatLon form is faster (one fewer field
  to copy) and the ellipsoid choice can be explicit per call.

REPRESENTATION

  latitude_radians   - latitude in RADIANS (north positive, range
                       [-pi/2, +pi/2]). Stored in radians because
                       almost every algorithm consuming the LatLon
                       first converts to radians.
  longitude_radians  - longitude in RADIANS (east positive, range
                       [-pi, +pi]). Stored in radians.
  ellipsoid_id       - Integer tag identifying the reference ellipsoid
                       (see ellipsoid.runa::ellipsoid_id_*).

ALGORITHMS

  haversine_distance(a, b)   - Great-circle distance on the sphere of
                                mean radius equal to the WGS84 mean
                                radius (6371008.7714 m). Spherical
                                approximation, accurate to ~ 0.5%.

  vincenty_distance(a, b)    - Geodesic distance on the ellipsoid using
                                Vincenty's iterative formula (1975).
                                Converges to < 0.5mm for almost any
                                pair of points. Returns -1.0 to signal
                                non-convergence for nearly-antipodal
                                pairs (the caller should fall back to
                                haversine in that case).

  initial_bearing(a, b)      - Forward azimuth at a heading toward b
                                along the great circle, in radians,
                                in the range [0, 2*pi).

  destination_point(p, b, d) - Direct geodesic problem: given start p,
                                initial bearing b (radians), and distance
                                d (metres), compute the destination.
                                Uses spherical formulae on the mean-radius
                                sphere (matching haversine_distance).

  midpoint(a, b)             - Great-circle midpoint of the two points.

  antipode(p)                - The point diametrically opposite p on the
                                Earth's surface.

CITATIONS

  - Sinnott, R. W. (1984): "Virtues of the haversine", Sky and Telescope
    68(2), 159.
  - Vincenty, T. (1975): "Direct and inverse solutions of geodesics on
    the ellipsoid with application of nested equations", Survey Review
    23(176), 88-93.
  - Williams, E. (2002): "Aviation formulary V1.46", widely used reference
    that compiles spherical-Earth navigation formulae.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/coordinate_reference_system.runa" as CRS
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/ellipsoid.runa" as Ellipsoid

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - LatLon struct and constructors
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "LatLon":
    latitude_radians as Float
    longitude_radians as Float
    ellipsoid_id as Integer
End Type

Process called "latlon_pi" returns Float:
    Return 3.141592653589793
End Process

Process called "latlon_two_pi" returns Float:
    Return 6.283185307179586
End Process

Process called "latlon_half_pi" returns Float:
    Return 1.5707963267948966
End Process

Process called "latlon_deg_to_rad_factor" returns Float:
    Note: pi / 180
    Return 0.017453292519943295
End Process

Process called "latlon_rad_to_deg_factor" returns Float:
    Note: 180 / pi
    Return 57.29577951308232
End Process

Process called "latlon_create" takes lat_deg as Float, lon_deg as Float, ellipsoid_id as Integer returns LatLon:
    @Reasoning:
        Primary constructor. Accepts degrees (the most common interchange
        format from GPS, GIS, and chart sources) and internally stores
        radians.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply both coordinates by pi / 180 and write into the
        struct.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two multiplies, three stores. ~ 10 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Out-of-range coordinates are stored verbatim - callers
        wanting validation should use latlon_create_validated below.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let factor be proc latlon_deg_to_rad_factor
    Let p be a value of type LatLon
    Set p.latitude_radians to lat_deg multiplied by factor
    Set p.longitude_radians to lon_deg multiplied by factor
    Set p.ellipsoid_id to ellipsoid_id
    Return p
End Process

Process called "latlon_create_wgs84" takes lat_deg as Float, lon_deg as Float returns LatLon:
    Note: Convenience overload defaulting to WGS84.
    Return proc latlon_create with lat_deg, lon_deg, (proc ellipsoid_id_wgs84 from Ellipsoid)
End Process

Process called "latlon_create_radians" takes lat_rad as Float, lon_rad as Float, ellipsoid_id as Integer returns LatLon:
    @Reasoning:
        Direct radian constructor. Used by destination_point and other
        algorithms whose internal state is already in radians.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Three stores, no scaling.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let p be a value of type LatLon
    Set p.latitude_radians to lat_rad
    Set p.longitude_radians to lon_rad
    Set p.ellipsoid_id to ellipsoid_id
    Return p
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Accessors and converters
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "latlon_latitude_radians" takes p as LatLon returns Float:
    Return p.latitude_radians
End Process

Process called "latlon_longitude_radians" takes p as LatLon returns Float:
    Return p.longitude_radians
End Process

Process called "latlon_latitude_degrees" takes p as LatLon returns Float:
    Return p.latitude_radians multiplied by (proc latlon_rad_to_deg_factor)
End Process

Process called "latlon_longitude_degrees" takes p as LatLon returns Float:
    Return p.longitude_radians multiplied by (proc latlon_rad_to_deg_factor)
End Process

Process called "latlon_ellipsoid_id" takes p as LatLon returns Integer:
    Return p.ellipsoid_id
End Process

Process called "latlon_to_degrees" takes p as LatLon returns LatLon:
    @Reasoning:
        Return a new LatLon whose stored fields are the degree-form
        rather than the radian-form. Useful for serialization paths
        where degrees are the desired interchange representation.
        The result is conceptually a (lat_deg, lon_deg) pair packaged
        in the same struct for caller convenience.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply both fields by 180/pi.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 10 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let factor be proc latlon_rad_to_deg_factor
    Let q be a value of type LatLon
    Set q.latitude_radians to p.latitude_radians multiplied by factor
    Set q.longitude_radians to p.longitude_radians multiplied by factor
    Set q.ellipsoid_id to p.ellipsoid_id
    Return q
End Process

Process called "latlon_to_radians" takes p as LatLon returns LatLon:
    Note: LatLon already stores radians; this is the identity for
    Note: API symmetry with latlon_to_degrees.
    Let q be a value of type LatLon
    Set q.latitude_radians to p.latitude_radians
    Set q.longitude_radians to p.longitude_radians
    Set q.ellipsoid_id to p.ellipsoid_id
    Return q
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Haversine distance
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "earth_mean_radius_wgs84_m" returns Float:
    Note: IUGG 1980 mean radius for WGS84: (2a + b) / 3 = 6371008.7714 m.
    Return 6371008.7714
End Process

Process called "haversine_distance" takes a as LatLon, b as LatLon returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Spherical great-circle distance using the haversine reformulation.
        Returns metres assuming the WGS84 mean radius. Accurate to
        ~ 0.5% for any pair of points on Earth.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        h = sin^2(dphi/2) + cos(phi_a) * cos(phi_b) * sin^2(dlambda/2)
        c = 2 * asin(sqrt(h))
        d = R * c
        We delegate sin / cos / asin to the CRS module's Float-typed
        wrappers (geo_sin, geo_cos, geo_asin) for consistency with the
        rest of the geo modules.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 200 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Antipodal points produce h = 1 which is the valid maximum
        for asin and yields d = pi * R = ~ 20015 km.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let phi_a be a.latitude_radians
    Let phi_b be b.latitude_radians
    Let dphi be phi_b minus phi_a
    Let dlam be b.longitude_radians minus a.longitude_radians
    Let sin_half_dphi be proc geo_sin from CRS with (dphi divided by 2.0)
    Let sin_half_dlam be proc geo_sin from CRS with (dlam divided by 2.0)
    Let cos_phi_a be proc geo_cos from CRS with phi_a
    Let cos_phi_b be proc geo_cos from CRS with phi_b
    Let a_term be sin_half_dphi multiplied by sin_half_dphi
    Let b_term be cos_phi_a multiplied by cos_phi_b
    Set b_term to b_term multiplied by sin_half_dlam
    Set b_term to b_term multiplied by sin_half_dlam
    Let h be a_term plus b_term
    Let sqrt_h be proc sqrt from Arith with h
    Let c_central be proc geo_asin from CRS with sqrt_h
    Set c_central to 2.0 multiplied by c_central
    Return (proc earth_mean_radius_wgs84_m) multiplied by c_central
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Vincenty inverse (ellipsoidal distance)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "vincenty_distance" takes p1 as LatLon, p2 as LatLon returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Vincenty's inverse formula for the geodesic distance between
        two points on an ellipsoid (Vincenty 1975). Iterates an
        auxiliary longitude difference lambda until it converges to
        within 1e-12 radians. Returns the distance in metres.
        Returns -1.0 if the iteration fails to converge within 200
        iterations (this happens for nearly-antipodal point pairs;
        Karney's algorithm is more robust in that regime).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Standard Vincenty inverse. Uses the ellipsoid associated with
        p1; if p1 and p2 have different ellipsoids we use p1's. The
        sigma, sin_sigma, cos_sigma, etc. are kept in named locals for
        readability. The series expansions for A and B use the Helmert
        Wladimir formula 4.21 in modified form for u_squared.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Each iteration is ~ 200 cycles (six trig calls + arithmetic).
        Typical convergence: 4-6 iterations. Worst case 200 iterations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Returns -1.0 sentinel on non-convergence.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ell be proc ellipsoid_get from Ellipsoid with p1.ellipsoid_id
    Note: Use the typed accessor procedures rather than direct cross-module
    Note: struct-field reads. Stage1 cannot infer the Float type of fields
    Note: defined in another module, so direct reads silently get treated
    Note: as Integer for the subsequent arithmetic, which produces NaN or
    Note: huge garbage values.
    Let a_axis be proc ellipsoid_semi_major_axis from Ellipsoid with ell
    Let b_axis be proc ellipsoid_semi_minor_axis from Ellipsoid with ell
    Let f be proc ellipsoid_flattening from Ellipsoid with ell
    Let L be p2.longitude_radians minus p1.longitude_radians
    Let U1 be proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with ((1.0 minus f) multiplied by (proc geo_sin from CRS with p1.latitude_radians)), (proc geo_cos from CRS with p1.latitude_radians)
    Let U2 be proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with ((1.0 minus f) multiplied by (proc geo_sin from CRS with p2.latitude_radians)), (proc geo_cos from CRS with p2.latitude_radians)
    Let sin_U1 be proc geo_sin from CRS with U1
    Let cos_U1 be proc geo_cos from CRS with U1
    Let sin_U2 be proc geo_sin from CRS with U2
    Let cos_U2 be proc geo_cos from CRS with U2
    Let lambda be L
    Let lambda_prev be 0.0
    Let iter_count be 0
    Let sin_sigma be 0.0
    Let cos_sigma be 0.0
    Let sigma be 0.0
    Let sin_alpha be 0.0
    Let cos_sq_alpha be 0.0
    Let cos_2sigma_m be 0.0
    Let converged be 0
    While iter_count is less than 200:
        Let sin_lambda be proc geo_sin from CRS with lambda
        Let cos_lambda be proc geo_cos from CRS with lambda
        Let t1 be cos_U2 multiplied by sin_lambda
        Let t2 be cos_U1 multiplied by sin_U2
        Set t2 to t2 minus (sin_U1 multiplied by cos_U2 multiplied by cos_lambda)
        Set sin_sigma to proc sqrt from Arith with ((t1 multiplied by t1) plus (t2 multiplied by t2))
        If sin_sigma is equal to 0.0:
            Return 0.0
        End If
        Set cos_sigma to (sin_U1 multiplied by sin_U2) plus (cos_U1 multiplied by cos_U2 multiplied by cos_lambda)
        Set sigma to proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with sin_sigma, cos_sigma
        Set sin_alpha to (cos_U1 multiplied by cos_U2 multiplied by sin_lambda) divided by sin_sigma
        Set cos_sq_alpha to 1.0 minus (sin_alpha multiplied by sin_alpha)
        If cos_sq_alpha is equal to 0.0:
            Set cos_2sigma_m to 0.0
        Otherwise:
            Set cos_2sigma_m to cos_sigma minus ((2.0 multiplied by sin_U1 multiplied by sin_U2) divided by cos_sq_alpha)
        End If
        Let C_coeff be (f divided by 16.0) multiplied by cos_sq_alpha
        Set C_coeff to C_coeff multiplied by (4.0 plus (f multiplied by (4.0 minus (3.0 multiplied by cos_sq_alpha))))
        Set lambda_prev to lambda
        Let inner be (2.0 multiplied by cos_2sigma_m multiplied by cos_2sigma_m) minus 1.0
        Let bracket be cos_2sigma_m plus (C_coeff multiplied by cos_sigma multiplied by inner)
        Set bracket to sigma plus (C_coeff multiplied by sin_sigma multiplied by bracket)
        Set lambda to L plus ((1.0 minus C_coeff) multiplied by f multiplied by sin_alpha multiplied by bracket)
        Let diff be lambda minus lambda_prev
        If diff is less than 0.0:
            Set diff to 0.0 minus diff
        End If
        If diff is less than 0.000000000001:
            Set converged to 1
            Set iter_count to 200
        Otherwise:
            Set iter_count to iter_count plus 1
        End If
    End While
    If converged is equal to 0:
        Return 0.0 minus 1.0
    End If
    Let u_sq be cos_sq_alpha multiplied by (((a_axis multiplied by a_axis) minus (b_axis multiplied by b_axis)) divided by (b_axis multiplied by b_axis))
    Note: A_coeff = 1 + (u_sq/16384) * (4096 + u_sq*(-768 + u_sq*(320 - 175*u_sq))).
    Note: Reverse-Horner from innermost outward.
    Let A_coeff be 320.0 minus (175.0 multiplied by u_sq)
    Set A_coeff to A_coeff multiplied by u_sq
    Set A_coeff to A_coeff minus 768.0
    Set A_coeff to A_coeff multiplied by u_sq
    Set A_coeff to A_coeff plus 4096.0
    Set A_coeff to A_coeff multiplied by u_sq
    Set A_coeff to A_coeff divided by 16384.0
    Set A_coeff to 1.0 plus A_coeff
    Note: B_coeff = (u_sq/1024) * (256 + u_sq*(-128 + u_sq*(74 - 47*u_sq))).
    Let B_coeff be 74.0 minus (47.0 multiplied by u_sq)
    Set B_coeff to B_coeff multiplied by u_sq
    Set B_coeff to B_coeff minus 128.0
    Set B_coeff to B_coeff multiplied by u_sq
    Set B_coeff to B_coeff plus 256.0
    Set B_coeff to B_coeff multiplied by u_sq
    Set B_coeff to B_coeff divided by 1024.0
    Let cos_2sigma_m_sq be cos_2sigma_m multiplied by cos_2sigma_m
    Let term_a be cos_sigma multiplied by ((2.0 multiplied by cos_2sigma_m_sq) minus 1.0)
    Let four_cos_sigma_sq be (4.0 multiplied by sin_sigma multiplied by sin_sigma) minus 3.0
    Let term_b be (B_coeff divided by 6.0) multiplied by cos_2sigma_m
    Set term_b to term_b multiplied by four_cos_sigma_sq
    Set term_b to term_b multiplied by ((4.0 multiplied by cos_2sigma_m_sq) minus 3.0)
    Let delta_sigma be (B_coeff divided by 4.0) multiplied by (term_a minus term_b)
    Set delta_sigma to sin_sigma multiplied by (cos_2sigma_m plus delta_sigma)
    Set delta_sigma to B_coeff multiplied by delta_sigma
    Let s be b_axis multiplied by A_coeff multiplied by (sigma minus delta_sigma)
    Return s
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - Bearing and destination
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "initial_bearing" takes a as LatLon, b as LatLon returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Forward azimuth at a heading toward b along the great-circle.
        Returns radians in [0, 2*pi).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        theta = atan2(sin(dlam) * cos(phi_b),
                      cos(phi_a) * sin(phi_b) - sin(phi_a) * cos(phi_b) * cos(dlam))
        Normalize negative results by adding 2*pi.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 250 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let phi_a be a.latitude_radians
    Let phi_b be b.latitude_radians
    Let dlam be b.longitude_radians minus a.longitude_radians
    Let sin_phi_a be proc geo_sin from CRS with phi_a
    Let cos_phi_a be proc geo_cos from CRS with phi_a
    Let sin_phi_b be proc geo_sin from CRS with phi_b
    Let cos_phi_b be proc geo_cos from CRS with phi_b
    Let sin_dlam be proc geo_sin from CRS with dlam
    Let cos_dlam be proc geo_cos from CRS with dlam
    Let y_val be sin_dlam multiplied by cos_phi_b
    Let x_val be (cos_phi_a multiplied by sin_phi_b) minus (sin_phi_a multiplied by cos_phi_b multiplied by cos_dlam)
    Let theta be proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with y_val, x_val
    If theta is less than 0.0:
        Set theta to theta plus (proc latlon_two_pi)
    End If
    Return theta
End Process

Process called "destination_point" takes start as LatLon, bearing_radians as Float, distance_metres as Float returns LatLon:
    @Reasoning:
        Direct geodesic problem on the spherical Earth: given a start
        point, an initial bearing, and a distance, compute the destination.
        Uses the WGS84 mean radius (spherical approximation).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Standard spherical-Earth direct formula:
          phi_dest = asin(sin(phi_1)*cos(d/R) + cos(phi_1)*sin(d/R)*cos(theta))
          lambda_dest = lambda_1 + atan2(sin(theta)*sin(d/R)*cos(phi_1),
                                          cos(d/R) - sin(phi_1)*sin(phi_dest))
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 350 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Negative distance is interpreted as the reverse direction
        which gives a meaningful result mathematically (i.e. moves
        backward along the great circle).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let R be proc earth_mean_radius_wgs84_m
    Let d_over_R be distance_metres divided by R
    Let sin_phi_1 be proc geo_sin from CRS with start.latitude_radians
    Let cos_phi_1 be proc geo_cos from CRS with start.latitude_radians
    Let sin_d_R be proc geo_sin from CRS with d_over_R
    Let cos_d_R be proc geo_cos from CRS with d_over_R
    Let sin_theta be proc geo_sin from CRS with bearing_radians
    Let cos_theta be proc geo_cos from CRS with bearing_radians
    Let sin_phi_dest be (sin_phi_1 multiplied by cos_d_R) plus (cos_phi_1 multiplied by sin_d_R multiplied by cos_theta)
    Let phi_dest be proc geo_asin from CRS with sin_phi_dest
    Let y_dest be sin_theta multiplied by sin_d_R multiplied by cos_phi_1
    Let x_dest be cos_d_R minus (sin_phi_1 multiplied by sin_phi_dest)
    Let dlam be proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with y_dest, x_dest
    Let lambda_dest be start.longitude_radians plus dlam
    Return proc latlon_create_radians with phi_dest, lambda_dest, start.ellipsoid_id
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - Midpoint and antipode
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "midpoint" takes a as LatLon, b as LatLon returns LatLon:
    @Reasoning:
        Great-circle midpoint of two points. Uses the standard
        Bx, By auxiliary formulation.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Bx = cos(phi_b) * cos(dlam)
        By = cos(phi_b) * sin(dlam)
        phi_m = atan2(sin(phi_a) + sin(phi_b),
                      sqrt((cos(phi_a) + Bx)^2 + By^2))
        lambda_m = lambda_a + atan2(By, cos(phi_a) + Bx)
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 350 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Antipodal points have an undefined midpoint; the formula
        returns the midpoint of one of the two equal great-circle arcs.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let phi_a be a.latitude_radians
    Let phi_b be b.latitude_radians
    Let dlam be b.longitude_radians minus a.longitude_radians
    Let sin_phi_a be proc geo_sin from CRS with phi_a
    Let cos_phi_a be proc geo_cos from CRS with phi_a
    Let sin_phi_b be proc geo_sin from CRS with phi_b
    Let cos_phi_b be proc geo_cos from CRS with phi_b
    Let cos_dlam be proc geo_cos from CRS with dlam
    Let sin_dlam be proc geo_sin from CRS with dlam
    Let Bx be cos_phi_b multiplied by cos_dlam
    Let By be cos_phi_b multiplied by sin_dlam
    Let y_num be sin_phi_a plus sin_phi_b
    Let inner be cos_phi_a plus Bx
    Let x_den be proc sqrt from Arith with ((inner multiplied by inner) plus (By multiplied by By))
    Let phi_m be proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with y_num, x_den
    Let lambda_offset be proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with By, inner
    Let lambda_m be a.longitude_radians plus lambda_offset
    Return proc latlon_create_radians with phi_m, lambda_m, a.ellipsoid_id
End Process

Process called "antipode" takes p as LatLon returns LatLon:
    @Reasoning:
        Antipode: the point diametrically opposite p on the Earth.
        latitude is negated and longitude is shifted by pi (wrapping
        to [-pi, +pi]).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        phi_anti = -phi
        lambda_anti = lambda + pi, normalised to [-pi, +pi]
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 10 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let new_lat be 0.0 minus p.latitude_radians
    Let new_lon be p.longitude_radians plus (proc latlon_pi)
    If new_lon is greater than (proc latlon_pi):
        Set new_lon to new_lon minus (proc latlon_two_pi)
    End If
    If new_lon is less than (0.0 minus (proc latlon_pi)):
        Set new_lon to new_lon plus (proc latlon_two_pi)
    End If
    Return proc latlon_create_radians with new_lat, new_lon, p.ellipsoid_id
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7 - Predicates
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "latlon_equals" takes a as LatLon, b as LatLon returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Structural equality including the ellipsoid.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Three field comparisons.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 10 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a.latitude_radians is not equal to b.latitude_radians:
        Return 0
    End If
    If a.longitude_radians is not equal to b.longitude_radians:
        Return 0
    End If
    If a.ellipsoid_id is not equal to b.ellipsoid_id:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "latlon_equals_within_tolerance" takes a as LatLon, b as LatLon, tolerance_radians as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Approximate equality of two LatLons within a tolerance.
        Useful for KAT-style assertions on geodesic computations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Absolute differences on each axis must fall within tolerance.
        The ellipsoid_id is ignored (the caller might compare across
        compatible ellipsoids).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 20 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dlat be a.latitude_radians minus b.latitude_radians
    If dlat is less than 0.0:
        Set dlat to 0.0 minus dlat
    End If
    If dlat is greater than tolerance_radians:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dlon be a.longitude_radians minus b.longitude_radians
    If dlon is less than 0.0:
        Set dlon to 0.0 minus dlon
    End If
    If dlon is greater than tolerance_radians:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process
